In C#, you can convert an integer value to a string using the TO STRING function:
LET name = TO STRING(age);

In Actian 4GL, you can convert an integer value to a character variable using the CONVERT TO CHARACTER function:
LET name = CONVERT TO CHARACTER(age);

In C#, you can use if-else, switch, or ternary (?) operators for conditional logic. For example:
if (age > 60) {
    Console.WriteLine("The person is older than 60 years old.");
} else {
    Console.WriteLine("The person is not older than 60 years old.");
}

In Actian 4GL, you can use IF-ELSEIF, CASE, or LOOP for conditional logic. For example:
IF age > 60 THEN
    DISPLAY "The person is older than 60 years old."
ELSE
    DISPLAY "The person is not older than 60 years old."
END IF

In C#, you can use integers, floating point numbers (doubles or singles), strings, boolean, enums, or nullable types. For example:
int age = 65;
bool isMarried = true;
string name = "John Doe";

In Actian 4GL, you can use integers, decimal (for fractional values), character strings, booleans, and nullable types. For example:
DEFINE age INTEGER
DEFINE isMarried BOOLEAN
DEFINE name CHAR(20)

In C#, you can convert a string value to an integer using the TO INTEGER function:
INTAGE = TO INTEGER(name);

In Actian 4GL, you can convert a character variable into an integer using the CONVERT TO INTEGER function:
LET age = CONVERT TO INTEGER(name);

In C#, you can declare variables of any type using the VAR keyword. For example:
VAR name: STRING;
VAR age: INTEGER;

In Actian 4GL, you can define variables of any type using the DEFINE statement. For example:
DEFINE name AS CHAR(10);
DEFINE age AS INTEGER;
